Contract performance management:
During the period from the date of the Contract until Practical Completion, the Contractor shall provide a monthly progress report to the Superintendent (Progress Report), draft by the 25th Business Day of month being reported and final by 3rd Business Day of following month in such format as agreed and/or required by the Superintendent.
Further to Clause 1.3.2. of QR-CTS-Part 1, the Progress Report shall include the following (as a minimum) for the relevant month:
• The updated Program showing progress to date.
• The progress made by the Contractor in the previous month in respect of the work under contract compared with the progress projected under the Program for the previous month and the progress required in order achieving, for each site loop, Practical Completion by the Date for Practical Completion for each site.
• The course of action that the Contractor proposes to undertake in response to any significant delays that have occurred to the work under contract during the previous month to ensure that the work under contract will thereafter be carried out in accordance with the Program and the terms of the Contract.
• Any act, matter or thing which has or is likely to have a material adverse effect together with detailed particulars on how the Contractor is dealing with any such issue, regarding the progress of the work under contract the interface of the work under contract with any other works or development being carried out or proposed to be carried out within or near the Site.
• Details of any identified risks and opportunities relating to the work under contract that may affect the time or cost of the work under contract.
• A copy of an updated index of the quality records, including all non-conformances identified under the Quality Plan together with the dispositions, authorisations and corrective actions undertaken.
• A report on the status of all Management Plans, copies of any modifications made to any Management Plan and a report on any non-conformances identified under any Management Plan.
• A report on the Contractor's performance against the requirements of the Construction Environmental Management Plan(s), including the status of compliance with the Environmental Documents.
• A summary of all reports and submissions sent to Authorities during the previous month.
• Lessons Learnt.
• Local content.
• Defect rectification.
• A summary of any safety and/or environmental incidents, traffic accidents recorded at the Site and any other relative safety and environmental statistic that shows that the work under contract is being undertaken in accordance with the Work Health and Safety Management Plan and Construction Environmental Management Plan(s).
• Photographic records, using date marked photography, showing (on a regular basis) construction progress.
• Requests for Information / Clarification register
• Variations and potential variations register
• Extensions of Time / Delays and potential claims register
• Progress Payments summary to date
• Summary of resource and procurement planning;
• A summary of Stakeholder interactions;
• Details of any complaints and actions;
• Results of any audits or regulatory authority visits;

Evaluation criteria and weightings:
COMPANY OVERVIEW & EXPERIENCE - 15%
KEY PERSONNEL - 15%
CAPABILITY & CAPACITY - 15%
EQUIPMENT - 15%
LOCAL BENEFITS - 10%

Deliverables: Strategic elimination of life-expired steel sleepers and fouled ballast; and replacement with new Full Depth Concrete (FDC) sleepers and ‘A’ grade ballast throughout several high priority locations on the Mt Isa main line.

Contract performance management:
The Static Frequency Converter (SFC) Contractor shall design, install, and commission the Static Frequency Converter Equipment awarded.
The SFC Contractor will complete the designs and specifications of the SFC related civil and structural works required to accommodate the entire SFC installation. These appropriately approved documents will be provided at IFC stage to the Purchaser as per the OMP. The Purchaser will appoint a Construction Integration Contractor to construct the required installation to this design and Specification.
SFC components shall be assembled/installed under the scope of the SFC Contractor, but where required, utilise conduits constructed and installed by the Construction Integrator Contractor (e.g. field wiring to transformers, cooling plant etc.). The SFC Contractor shall supply all cables which interface between SFC components.
The SFC Contractor shall specify their requirements for all SFC related interfaces which will be co-ordinated with other Equipment vendors by the Purchaser, and installed under the responsibility of the Construction Integrator.

Deliverables:
Auchenflower and Cannon Hill Stations are part of a rolling program of accessibility upgrades being delivered by Queensland Rail with the aim of improving accessibility at several stations across the Southeast Queensland (SEQ) network. 
The projects' objective is to make the station independently accessible along the primary path of travel (PPT), ensuring compliance with all relevant codes and standards. 
Improvements to the stations include a new footbridge and lifts, high level platforms to provide easier access where the assisted boarding point is located, and extended waiting shelters. The upgrade also includes a range of other accessibility features such as hearing augmentation loops, wayfinding information and signage, improved lighting, and security.
Contract milestones:
Possession of Site is given on and from 02 July 2020 (Auchenflower) and 17 July 2020 (Cannon Hill), (or as directed by the Superintendent) and provided all contractual obligations that are prerequisite to the commencement of Works have been met to the satisfaction and acceptance of the Superintendent. The Date for Practical Completion for each Separable Portion is as follows:
•	Separable Portion 1 Auchenflower - 13 April 2022
•	Separable Portion 2 Cannon Hill - 21 September 2021
Contract performance management:
The Contractor shall carry out and complete works under contract in accordance with the Contract and Directions authorised by the Contract.
The Principal shall pay the Contractor:
a) for work for which the Principal accepted a lump sum, the lump sum; and
b) for work for which the Principal accepted rates, the sum of the products ascertained by multiplying the measured quantity of each section or item of work actually carried out under the Contract by the rate accepted by the Principal for the section or item, adjusted by any additions or deductions made pursuant to the Contract.

Deliverables: The TLS Deed provides for the preventive and corrective maintenance and support of the installed ETCS provided by Hitachi under the ETCS Project Deed, including software and hardware-specific maintenance and support and the provision of updates, new releases and spare parts. The TLS Deed provides for a collaborative approach to the delivery of the TLS activities where staff from Hitachi will work in parallel with Queensland Rail staff to undertake the maintenance activities within the TLS Deed whilst upskilling Queensland Rail staff.
Contract performance management:
During the TLS support period the integrated systems will be primarily be maintained by QR’s LoR1 and LoR2 teams, and supported by STS LoR1 and LoR2 resources as required, to provide the necessary safety assurances of the ETCS System. The objectives of the TLS are to:
1. Ensuring Safety Integrity of QR’s Rail Network
2. Minimising Impacts to Operations that could affect production
3. Supporting the availability of the ETCS L2 system in operation
4. Supporting the transition of QR staff maintaining the ETCS L2 system autonomously
As the field systems are to be delivered in phases and with fit out progressing prior to the completion of all system deliveries, additional considerations are needed to comply with the points above.
Specifically, both the inclusion of regular Periodic Preventative Maintenance procedures to satisfy Safety, as well as Preventative and Corrective Maintenance procedures to minimise production impacts and support the operational phased deployment of the ETCS L2 system, are required.
For Preventative Maintenance, the Section 8 Indicative Preventative Maintenance Tasks Lists are intended to provide the necessary coverage to maintain the integrity of the system operation.
For Corrective Maintenance these shall be prioritised based on operational impact identified at the time of the fault. These faults will be tracked using QR’s Enterprise Asset Management System (EAMS).
A spare parts analysis will be conducted following the Project RAM Analysis to support the spares requirements for the TLS period.

Contract description/name: Brakes, Pneumatics, Couplers, HVAC, doors, Body/fittings
Evaluation criteria and weightings: Negotiation of supply
Deliverables: Provision of Overhaul and Original Equipment Manufacturer (OEM) Parts
Contract performance management:
1.	Contract Program 
Where the Contract Particulars specify that a program is required, the Contractor must:
(a)	prepare and obtain Queensland Rail's approval of a program for the Supply (in a form approved by Queensland Rail) before commencing the Supply; 
(b)	at all times comply with the approved program; and
(c)	not change the program without Queensland Rail's prior written approval.

2.	Scope of the Contract
The Contractor must, as an independent contractor:
(a)	carry out the Supply; and
(b)	at the Contractor's own cost, supply all labour, materials, services, goods, plant, equipment or other things necessary to provide the Goods or Services (whether or not expressly described in the Contract) or comply with its obligations under the Contract.

3.	Laws and regulations
3.1	Compliance with the law and other requirements
The Contractor must:
(a)	comply with:
(i)	all Relevant Laws and Government Consents applicable to the Supply;
(ii)	regulations, rules, schemes or plans issued by Queensland Rail governing Site activities, industrial relations, construction, safety and the environment (including the policies referred to in section 2 of Schedule 5), and Queensland Rail's Corporate Policies applicable to the Supply; and
(b)	obtain and maintain all Government Consents in connection with the Supply; and
(c)	pay any fees, charges, levies and taxes imposed by an Authority in relation to the Supply.
The cost of complying with this clause 3.1 is included in the Contract Price. 
3.2	DDA Act compliance  
Without limiting clause 3.1, the Contractor:
(a)	acknowledges Queensland Rail is required to comply with the Disability Discrimination Act 1992 (Cth) (DDA Act); and
(b)	must ensure the Supply is compliant with the DDA Act.

4.	Quality of materials and Goods used in the Supply
All materials and Goods supplied by the Contractor must:
(a)	be of merchantable quality and fit for their intended purpose;
(b)	be free from all defects and imperfections affecting performance;
(c)	be of current manufacture, appropriate grade and suitable capacity; and 
(d)	comply with the Scope of Supply.

5.	Queensland Rail supplied materials
The Contractor must use any property, goods, materials, services or information provided by Queensland Rail:
(a)	at its own risk;
(b)	only to provide the Supply;
(c)	using reasonable care; and
(d)	in accordance with Queensland Rail's instructions.
